articles.headline: How every five-star college football recruit fits at his new school
articles.description: There are 21 five-stars in the Class of 2026. We look at how they got to their teams and what they'll do in college.

articles.headline: Jaden O'Neal gives Florida State highest-rated QB since 2022 class
articles.description: Four-star quarterback Jaden O'Neal, ranked No. 112 in the 2026 ESPN 300, announced his commitment to Florida State on Sunday night, sealing a long-anticipated flip for the former Oklahoma pledge.

articles.headline: Defensive end Richard Wesley commits to Texas Longhorns
articles.description: Defensive end Richard Wesley, a 6-foot-5, 250-pound pass rusher from Chatsworth, California, has committed to Texas, the No. 18 overall prospect in the 2026 ESPN 300 announced on Sunday night following an official visit with the Longhorns this weekend.

articles.headline: Ex-Buckeye Kirk Barton facing charge after fatal crash in Ohio
articles.description: Kirk Barton, a former captain at Ohio State who went on to play in the NFL, faces an aggravated vehicular manslaughter charge following a fatal crash early Saturday morning.

articles.headline: Notre Dame lands commitments from Khary Adams, Joey O'Brien
articles.description: Notre Dame landed pledges from a pair of top 2026 defensive back targets Friday, edging a trio of recruiting rivals to the commitments of No. 8 cornerback Khary Adams and No. 4 athlete prospect Joey O'Brien.

articles.headline: Oklahoma fills need with commitment of 4-star QB Bowe Bentley
articles.description: Four-star quarterback Bowe Bentley, No. 261 in the 2026 ESPN 300, announced his commitment to Oklahoma over LSU on Friday.

article.headline: La Tech plays for 1st time since Halloween, tops North Texas
article.description: — Israel Tucker carried it 37 times for 161 yards and two touchdowns, and Louisiana Tech beat North Texas 42-31 on Thursday night in its first game since Halloween.
article.linkText: La Tech plays for 1st time since Halloween, tops North Texas
article.story: DENTON, Texas -- — Israel Tucker carried it 37 times for 161 yards and two touchdowns, and Louisiana Tech beat North Texas 42-31 on Thursday night in its first game since Halloween. Louisiana Tech (5-3, 4-2 Conference USA) hadn't played since a 37-34 double-overtime victory over UAB on Oct. 31. The Bulldogs had games canceled or postponed against North Texas, Rice, Louisiana-Monroe and Florida International. The Bulldogs are scheduled to play at TCU on Dec. 12. Louisiana Tech secured its fifth straight victory at North Texas. Luke Anthony passed for 110 yards and two touchdowns for Louisiana Tech, which has losses against No. 22 BYU, Marshall and West-leading UTSA. Smoke Harris caught seven passes for 40 yards and a touchdown, and Kyle Maxwell added a receiving TD. Jason Bean connected with Jaelon Darden on three touchdowns through the air for North Texas (3-5, 2-4). Bean, who was intercepted on the first possession of the game, threw for 231 yards with three touchdowns and one interception. Darden caught eight passes for 135 yards, and Nic Smith rushed for 96 yards. Darden had his third three-touchdown game of the season, giving him 15 receiving TDs to lead the FBS. He was tied going into the game with Alabama's DeVonta Smith and Arkansas State's Jonathan Adams. ------ More AP college football: https://apnews.com/hub/college-football and https://twitter.com/AP--Top25
